ion of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species followed by release into solution.", "reasoning": "Directly follows the provided hydrothermal framework that CO2 + H2 yields formate on greigite at 350-400K in alkaline vent settings; low-temperature submarine hydrothermal systems and alkaline vents are identified as favorable for amino-acid precursor synthesis. This step is used as a literature-grounded entry into reduced carbon chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; as summarized in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde-equivalent feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing, rock-water interaction"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction of C1 oxo-carbon species on Fe-bearing mineral surfaces produces methanal/formaldehyde-equivalent carbonyl feedstock.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature notes formaldehyde and ammonia as general prebiotic amino-acid precursors and highlights hydrothermal synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks, though not arginine-specific. This connection is therefore partially inferential but consistent with hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry and necessary to connect literature-supported precursor pools (Banez & Oros, 1971; Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; speculative connection explicitly added because arginine-specific steps are absent in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type carbon fixation to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent setting with CO/CO2/H2 mixtures; Fischer-Tropsch-type regime"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed C-C bond formation from reduced C1 species gives C2 carboxylates such as acetate.", "reasoning": "This matches the stated hydrothermal key reaction type that CO2 reduction can proceed to acetate and that magnetite supports Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis. It builds the reduced carbon inventory relevant to downstream alpha-keto acid formation in hydrothermal systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; summarized hydrothermal framework in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent to subseafloor interface, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-assisted carbon fixation and condensation convert reduced C1/C2 species into the central alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The supplied instructions explicitly list pyruvate synthesis from CO2 + H2 on magnetite/greigite at 350-400K as a key hydrothermal reaction type. Because the literature compilation emphasizes alpha-keto acid and hydrothermal amino-acid precursor formation without detailing exact pyruvate stoichiometry, this network encodes pyruvate as a hydrothermal hub in a literature-consistent but generalized form (Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; provided hydrothermal reaction framework; connection is plausible but not arginine-specific)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface cyanide generation from reduced carbon-nitrogen chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic pool or geothermal field, reducing, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and redox-driven conversion of simple carbonyl/nitrogen feedstocks into cyanide-bearing species in surface pools.", "reasoning": "The provided report identifies cyanide-rich reducing environments containing H2S as plausible for arginine precursor synthesis and emphasizes UV photochemistry in surface settings. Exact arginine-specific HCN-generation chemistry was not supplied, so this step is a necessary connecting reaction that remains consistent with cyanosulfidic surface chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016; speculative connection justified by the report's cyanide-rich environment emphasis)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "UV-assisted hydration/rearrangement of HCN yields formamide as a versatile nitrogenous intermediate.", "reasoning": "This follows the provided surface reaction type 'HCN + H2O + UV -> formamide -> nucleobases.' Although not specific to arginine, formamide chemistry is a documented surface nitrogen reservoir and supports convergent nitrogen-rich prebiotic networks (Saladino et al., 2012; summary in provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Irradiation of ammonium cyanide to cyanamide/guanidino precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV or proton irradiation under anoxic surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Energetic irradiation of ammonium cyanide reorganizes C-N bonding to produce cyanamide-class guanidino precursors.", "reasoning": "The literature report explicitly states that irradiation of ammonium cyanide is a plausible prebiotic route to guanidine/guanidino-group formation. Cyanamide is used here as the immediate activated guanidino precursor because it is a classic prebiotic condensing/guanidinating agent and provides a chemically realistic link to arginine assembly; this is the closest literature-grounded route available from the supplied report (reported in Journal of Molecular Evolution source cited in the knowledge base; late-stage assignment to cyanamide is a necessary but partly interpretive connection)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Further conversion of cyanamide to guanidine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide/phosphate mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration with wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Ammonolysis/addition to cyanamide on mineral surfaces generates guanidine-like guanidino donors.", "reasoning": "The report supports guanidino-group formation from irradiated ammonium cyanide but does not provide an experimentally resolved incorporation sequence into amino acids. This step is therefore a speculative but chemically conservative extension to create a guanidino donor reservoir for arginine assembly (knowledge-base guanidino-group report; speculative connection required because no direct incorporation study was found)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface formose/aldol route to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite