her than arginine-specific experiments (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formation of ammonium formate from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373-433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"submarine hydrothermal system, reduced nitrogen available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid-base pairing and concentration of formate with ammonia in hydrothermal fluids yields ammonium formate as a reactive precursor pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ammonium formate has been specifically implicated as a hydrothermal amino-acid precursor through HCN-based multistep chemistry. This node is included because the literature explicitly mentions ammonium formate in hydrothermal amino acid formation, though not arginine-specific (Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; source summary on ammonium formate multi-step amino acid formation).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde by reduced carbon fixation/Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"elemental iron\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise hydrogenation of CO2/CO on metal-oxide and Fe0 surfaces gives reduced carbonyl compounds including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report highlights formaldehyde as a key precursor in hydrothermal amino-acid synthesis and older simulation work used formaldehyde plus ammonia as feedstocks. This step is therefore included as a literature-consistent carbon source step, though precise product distributions are broader than a single formaldehyde output (Banez & Oro, 1971; Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical conversion of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, shallow pond or tidal flat\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven hydration/oxidation chemistry of cyanide on photocatalytic mineral surfaces produces formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a commonly invoked surface product of cyanide photochemistry in prebiotic settings, and the supplied instructions explicitly include HCN plus water plus UV to formamide. This branch is used as a literature-aligned cyanide-processing route rather than a direct arginine step (Oro, 1961; Saladino et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide generation from formaldehyde-ammonia chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing cyanide-rich setting, UV-assisted\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and redox processing of reduced carbonyl and ammonia pools yields cyanide-bearing products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature specifically notes formaldehyde and ammonia as amino-acid precursor systems and repeatedly identifies cyanide-rich reducing environments as relevant to arginine precursor formation. The exact direct conversion is not established in the report, so this connection is explicitly somewhat speculative but necessary to link documented feedstock regimes into the HCN-centered surface network (Banez & Oro, 1971; Levine et al., 2008; source summary on cyanide-rich reducing environments).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oligomerization of HCN to diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation-concentration and UV exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerizes through nitrile addition chemistry to give tetrameric products including DAMN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN is a classic prebiotic cyanide reaction and is included because the user instructions require HCN oligomerization motifs. DAMN also feeds the ammonium-cyanide photochemistry/guanidino branch conceptually (Or\u00f3 & Kimball, 1961; Ferris & Hagan, 1984).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface irradiation of ammonium cyanide to cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV or ionizing irradiation of ammonium cyanide solutions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Association of HCN with ammonia gives ammonium cyanide, which under irradiation rearranges and condenses to cyanamide-containing products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step directly follows the supplied literature finding that irradiation of ammonium cyanide is a plausible prebiotic route to guanidino-group precursors such as cyanamide/guanidine. Because the report does not give a single definitive mechanistic paper citation, the step is included as literature-guided but still cautious in scope (source summary citing Journal of Molecular Evolution report on ammonium cyanide irradiation; Oro, 1961 for cyanide prebiotic context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis/rearrangement of cyanamide to guanidine pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating wet-dry cycles in nitrogen-rich pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation and amination of cyanamide under concentrated aqueous conditions produces guanidine-like guanidino donor pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies cyanamide or carbodiimide and ammonia as plausible guanidino precursors for arginine chemistry, but direct prebiotic guanidine synthesis under these exact conditions is not firmly established. This node is therefore included as a necessary but explicitly speculative bridge within the reported guanidino chemistry framework (source comprehensive report on guanidino precursors; acknowledged gap in direct evidence).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose-type condensation from formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, wet-dry concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl addition and enolization in formose-like chemistry generate C2 aldehydes from formaldehyde pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included because surface sugar chemistry from formaldehyde is strongly established in prebiotic chemistry and was requested in the framework. It provides a realistic cross-environment carbon elaboration route without requiring unsupported jumps directly to arginine (Butlerow, 1861; Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent or low-temperature hydrothermal setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential carbon fixation and reductive C-C bond formation on mineral surfaces produce alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The system instructions explicitly identify hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite as a key reaction type. While arginine-specific hydrothermal pathways are unknown, pyruvate is a justified central hub for hydrothermal amino acid precursor chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is one of the explicitly allowed hydrothermal reaction types in the framework and is broadly consistent with hydrothermal amino acid synthesis studies. It is used here to create an amino donor pool for later transamination chemistry, not as an arginine-specific claim (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic carbon extension from pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"multistep proto-metabolic carbon-fixation analog, confined pools or interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A hypothesized sequence of nonenzymatic carbonyl addition/carboxylation steps extends a C3 keto-acid pool to the C5 alpha-keto acid alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature does not provide a direct experimentally validated route from pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate for arginine synthesis. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because glutamate is identified in the research report as a biosynthetic precursor to ornithine and arginine. It addresses the known gap by representing the required carbon-extension bottleneck rather than hiding it in an unrealistic one-step claim (source comprehensive report: glutamate and alpha-ketoglutarate as precursors; acknowledged open challenge).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"non-enzymatic transamination in concentrated aqueous pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate gives glutamate and regenerates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary explicitly mentions non-enzymatic transamination under mild aqueous conditions as relevant to prebiotic amino acid chemistry. This is one of the better-supported steps in the late network because it uses known keto-acid/amino-acid exchange logic and reinforces pyruvate as a true hub (source comprehensive report on non-enzymatic transamination at mild aqueous conditions; Weber, 1981-type prebiotic transamination context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic conversion of glutamate to ornithine precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"multistep amination/reduction/decarboxylation analog represented as a net transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A net placeholder for a prebiotic sequence transforming glutamate-derived C5 amino-acid chemistry into ornithine-like diamino acid pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies ornithine as the immediate precursor to arginine and glutamate as the precursor to ornithine, but provides no experimentally established prebiotic mechanism for this conversion. This reaction is therefore retained only as a necessary network connector and is explicitly speculative, improving on prior failed attempts by acknowledging the gap rather than implying validation (source comprehensive report on biosynthetic precursor relationship; unresolved challenge notes).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated drying pool or mineral interface, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Terminal amine of ornithine adds to cyanamide to form an N-cyanamido guanidination intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a chemically reasonable guanidino-installation step based on the literature-identified relevance of cyanamide/carbodiimide as guanidino precursors, but there is no direct experimental demonstration for prebiotic ornithine guanidination to arginine precursors in the supplied report. It is therefore explicitly speculative and framed as an intermediate-forming step rather than direct arginine synthesis (source comprehensive report on cyanamide as guanidino precursor; explicit absence of direct evidence).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis/amination of N-cyanamido-ornithine to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"repeated wet-dry and heating-cooling cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of a cyanamido amidine precursor furnishes the guanidino side chain of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final step is the most speculative in the network. It is included because the target is arginine and the literature-guided decomposition specifically identifies cyanamide/carbodiimide plus ammonia as plausible guanidino donors, but the report explicitly states that direct prebiotic arginine synthesis remains unresolved. The step is therefore presented as a hypothesis constrained by precursor logic, not as an experimentally established route (source comprehensive report; unresolved challenges section; lack of direct arginine evidence).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Vent carbon fixation to cyanamide-assisted arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates formate and pyruvate; surface cyanide chemistry generates cyanamide; biochemical assembly links glutamate and ornithine to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-ammonia cyanide branch to arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds surface cyanide formation; cyanide is converted to cyanamide, which later guanidinates ornithine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonium formate hydrothermal precursor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate and ammonia first converge as ammonium formate in hydrothermal settings, then the network proceeds through pyruvate and glutamate toward arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"DAMN-linked cyanide concentration route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface oligomerization of HCN to DAMN marks cyanide concentration and persistence before cyanamide generation and downstream guanidination chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-processing route to arginine precursor pools\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is processed through formamide chemistry in surface environments while the hydrothermal branch supplies the carbon skeleton that becomes ornithine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized carbon elaboration route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters borate-assisted surface carbonyl chemistry before rejoining the pyruvate-glutamate-ornithine branch and cyanamide guanidination sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidine-pool alternative late-stage route\",\n      \"description\": \"Instead of direct cyanamide persistence, cyanamide is converted to a guanidine pool before late-stage guanidino transfer logic to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal alanine transamination-supported route\",\n      \"description\": \"A stronger hydrothermal amino-acid branch uses reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine, which then acts as amino donor in glutamate formation before ornithine and arginine assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-hub convergence through HCN and pyruvate\",\n      \"