ry citing Journal of Molecular Evolution report on ammonium cyanide irradiation to guanidine precursors).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of cyanamide to guanidine pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"nitrogen-rich evaporitic concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogen addition to cyanamide in concentrated aqueous films yields a guanidine-equivalent donor pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research clearly supports guanidino-group emergence from ammonium cyanide irradiation but does not provide a detailed experimentally demonstrated cyanamide-to-guanidine step for prebiotic arginine synthesis. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative but necessary to represent a plausible guanidino donor branch without claiming direct validation (research summary on guanidino-group formation; speculative connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose/aldol generation of glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of formaldehyde in borate-stabilized settings produces simple sugar precursors including glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a standard surface prebiotic sugar-chemistry step explicitly permitted by the prompt through formose and aldol condensation chemistry with borate minerals. It is included not as a direct arginine route but as an alternative carbon-expansion branch feeding later alpha-keto-acid speculation (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-style carbon expansion from pyruvate and glycolaldehyde to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool; nonenzymatic carbonyl chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential aldol-like carbon-carbon bond formation and oxidation-state reorganization are abstracted into a net conversion from pyruvate plus a C2 aldehyde to alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is an explicitly speculative network-connecting step. The provided literature mentions alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate as biosynthetic precursors to arginine and notes redox-sensitive pathways leading to alpha-ketoglutarate-related chemistry, but it does not establish this exact nonenzymatic conversion. It is retained only because previous attempts failed by hiding such speculation; here it is made explicit as the major unresolved bottleneck in moving from supported precursor chemistry to arginine-like backbones (research summary on alpha-ketoglutarate as precursor; speculative connector acknowledging unresolved carbon-expansion problem).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015