t honoring the literature-identified precursor logic (research summary structural decomposition of arginine; speculative connector acknowledging missing experimental support).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated drying-rewetting cycles in anoxic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Terminal amino group of ornithine adds to activated cyanamide-derived guanidino carbon, followed by proton transfer and hydrolysis to yield arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is not experimentally established in the supplied literature and was a principal weakness of earlier attempts. It is included only because the report identifies cyanamide/carbodiimide-like guanidino precursors and ornithine as the immediate precursor to arginine. The step is therefore a transparent hypothesis consistent with the literature\u2019s precursor decomposition but not directly validated (research summary structural decomposition and guanidino-group discussion; explicitly speculative).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative guanidination of ornithine by guanidine pool to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool with repeated heating/cooling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Guanidine-equivalent donor transfers a guanidino group to the terminal amino functionality of ornithine in a net condensation/substitution sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"As with rxn_016, no direct evidence for prebiotic incorporation of guanidino groups into amino acids is provided in the research. This alternative end-step is retained only as a parallel hypothesis because the report explicitly raises guanidine-type prebiotic chemistry from ammonium cyanide irradiation. It is less direct than rxn_016 and remains speculative (research summary on guanidino-group formation; explicitly speculative connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-to-biochemical HCN-assisted Strecker-like route to ornithine precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"multistep aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis abstracted as net route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto-acid-centered Strecker-like elaboration and side-chain homologation are abstracted as a net route from pyruvate, HCN, and ammonia to an ornithine-like diamino acid pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report emphasizes that Strecker chemistry is a general prebiotic amino-acid framework but also explicitly says arginine-specific Strecker intermediates are not available in the dataset. This reaction is therefore a deliberately marked abstract connector representing literature-supported general Strecker logic applied to the ornithine precursor problem, not a demonstrated single-step synthesis (Strecker, 1850 historical framework; research summary explicitly noting lack of arginine-specific Strecker detail and thus speculative extension).\"\n    }\n  ],